      • override

        protected IRNode override(IRNode parent,
                          IRNode n)
        Allows to hijack the traversal of a subtree. This function is called by visit(IRNode, IRNode) upon entering node n. If a non-null node n0 is returned, the traversal is stopped and the resulting AST has n0 in place of n. By default, overriding is inactive.

      • enter

        protected IRVisitor enter(IRNode parent,
                          IRNode n)
        Called upon entering n during the AST traversal. This allows to perform certain actions, including returning a new Node visitor to be used in the subtree.

      • leave

        protected IRNode leave(IRNode parent,
                       IRNode n,
                       IRNode n_,
                       IRVisitor v_)
        Called after finishing traversal of the subtree rooted at n. When enter(IRNode, IRNode) creates a new visitor to be used on the subtree, the old visitor still receives the call to leave() -- that is, leave() always executed the same number of times as enter(IRNode, IRNode). This node provides the final opportunity of placing an updated node in the output AST.
        Parameters:
        parent - The parent AST node of n or null when it is the root.
        n - The original node in the input AST
        n_ - The node returned by IRNode.visitChildren(IRVisitor)
        v_ - The new node visitor created by enter(IRNode, IRNode), or this.
